Camille Auer wanted to fix her sex, diagnosed as mentally ill, and now she's doing art on the subject - "People should have a right to their own body"
There are dozens of patient stories hanging from the ceiling of the Academy of Fine Arts Project room.
Every one of them says Camille Auer's name.
The papers tell a multi-year story about how outsiders have written down their interpretation of Auer and his identity.
Decided for him who he is.
"I wanted to tell my personal treatment history to make the violence in the process visible," Auer says.
By the process, he refers to the sex correction process.
It is often a period of years that includes meetings with psychologists, psychiatrists, nurses and doctors.
The process begins with a referral to diagnosis studies of "gender identity disorder" that are conducted in Tampere and Helsinki.
For Auer, the process started four years ago.
Even before that, she had used the estrogen she had ordered over the Internet and was already very advanced in her own repair process.
She felt she was a woman, but according to Finnish law, a person must undergo a correction process so that the gender can also be legally corrected.
Translakis, the law establishing the sex of transsek sual (563/2002), obliges transgender people to force sterilisation in order to get the right sex into, for example, a population register centre and passport.
At the moment, every sex repairer is required to have a psychiatric diagnosis and a certificate of reproductive inability.
A person has the right to decide on his own body.
"This situation is intolerable and violates human rights," Auer said.
The reform of the Translai law has been discussed in Finland for a long time.
The UN Human Rights Council has made eight observations about the law, and the European Court of Justice has a precedent that obliges the parties to the European Convention on Human Rights to respect their right to self-determination.
The previous Finnish government prepared a change in the law under the leadership of the then Minister of Social Affairs and Health Susanne Huovinen.
The elections came and the Finns Party rose to the board.
Now the bill change is stuck again.
It is a question of domestic political disputes that do not even have anything to do with this law.
"The board doesn't want to put it on the table because there are disagreements within the board about changing the law," says Frank Johansson, Executive Director of Amnesty Finland's department.
The front part of the exhibition space is dominated by two large installations.
One consists of the packaging and instructions for use of the medicines that Auer uses.
In the patient history installation, any visitor can read, for example, the interpretation of the transpol psychologist at Tampere University Hospital in Auer.
The psychologist met Camille Auer twice, and based on these, wrote a report that would define Auer's right to care and help.
The sense of the reality to be studied appears vulnerable to wavering.
The studyer's perception of himself appears to be fragmented in a border-level way, and the unstable personality features are highlighted.
Auer didn't recognize himself from these descriptions.
"It was a shock to hear that I was diagnosed as mentally ill," Auer said.
The shock was even greater when Auer was not given gender correction treatment.
According to the nursing staff, his resources were not enough to start the process.
He was denied his own identity.
On 11 February 2015, Auer walked out of the meeting and kicked the television in the waiting lobby of the transpol.
Later, that television created a work of art called Monument for the Exclusived, in which Auer reflected his experience of power and its use.
"It's crazy that any person who is defined as a woman at birth can enlarge their breasts, but a diagnosis is needed to remove the breasts," Auer says.
Your body is not yours if you feel you are anything other than the number of genders defined at birth.
Unfortunately, Auer's experience is not unique.
For many, the gender correction process is harder for mental reasons than for purely medical operations.
Those who go through it meet dozens of people who have to justify their own existence and their right to their own sexual experience.
"It's crazy that people who need support and help are denied treatment, arguing that their resources are not enough," Auer says.
Many of those seeking the process have psychological symptoms behind them: depression, anxiety, possible bullying experiences.
Based on these, the medical staff may order that the treatment cannot be started.
"To prevent treatment and help can put a person in an even worse situation than it was before the process started," Auer says.
Auer's personal exhibition also deals with anxiety and thoughts about suicide.
Auer writes: "I have had suicidal thoughts throughout my adult life and that is something people usually find difficult to digest."
Depression has been treated with drugs, and when Auer started using hormones, it got easier.
He had finally been able to lyric the feelings that had existed already in childhood and in teens.
Why the wide jaw didn't seem to fit into its own body and why the chest muscles had to be round instead of a flat chest.
The most important thing for Auer is that there are people around him who see him.
Being seen is a basic need.
"You have to justify yourself so much by talking, dressing, using sound and moving," he says.
Today Auer already feels seen, she exists as a woman.
At the beginning of the process, however, the random comments of close people could hurt a lot.
It hurts the most when people close to you are misgroomed.
"They should know who I am, and they know who I am, but they won't or will not be able to internalize it," he continues.
But not all transhumans need physical changes.
They do not suffer from body dysphoria, or body conflict, where the body or parts of it can cause anxiety and even physical pain.
However, without the use of hormones and the lengthy research process, there can be no formal confirmation of their own gender.
"There is no medical basis for these studies," Auer says.
And it's true.
In Denmark, for example, in June 2014, Parliament approved a new procedure for the recognition of the legal sex.
The new legislation is based on the right to self-determination in relation to legal sex.
An adult applicant submits a written application for a new personal identity code, stating that he or she feels that he or she is of the opposite sex.
After six months of reflection, the applicant confirms his application in writing and the Ministry gives the applicant a new personal identity code.
This self-determination is also required in Finland, and the Auer exhibition also sums up this requirement.
It has not been a therapy experience for the artist, but the exhibition is a political and artistic collection of works.
I want to believe that art still has weight and that it can bring about political changes, at a time when politicians have forgotten about human rights.
