The Civil Rights Organisation issued a travel warning to Missouri
The National NAACP for African-American civil rights has issued a travel warning for Missouri, due to discriminatory state practices and racist attacks there.
"The NACP's Missouri travel announcement comes into effect on 28 August 2017 and calls on African-American tourists, visitors and locals to pay special attention and to exercise extreme caution when travelling to a state where there have recently been a number of questionable racial events," the organisation's statement states.
The recent law in Missouri makes it more difficult to take discrimination cases to court, and the state's law enforcement is disproportionately targeted at minorities, which, according to NACP, led to a travel warning.
"People's civil rights are being violated.
They will be stopped based on skin colour and beaten or killed," Rod Chapel, president of NAACP Missouri, said to Kansas City Star.
"We've never heard of so many cases in such a short time."
The travel announcement about Missouri is the organisation's first warning about the state of the United States.
The organisation cited racist comments against African-American students at Missouri University and the death of 28-year-old black Tory Sanders from Tennessee.
Sanders died under questionable circumstances earlier this year, driving through the state when his car ran out of fuel, and was arrested by Missouri police, even though he was not charged with a crime.
The travel notice also referred to Missouri's Attorney General's report that police are 75 percent more likely to stop a black driver than a white one.
"The purpose of the travel information report is to advise people to be on guard and warn their families, friends and colleagues about what can happen in Missouri," Chapel says.
"People have to prepare, for example, by including money to pay bail or by telling relatives that they are going to travel through the state."
According to the FBI, 100 hate crimes were recorded in Missouri in 2015, the sixteenth largest in the United States.
The travel warning is also a response to Missouri's new law, which makes it more difficult to sue companies for discrimination in housing and employment relationships.
The ACLU organisation, which defends civil rights guaranteed by the Constitution, recently issued travel warnings to Texas and Arizona after they had passed immigration laws that force the police to arrest people for immigration violations, which, according to the organisation, increases racial profiling.
Usually travel warnings are published by the State Department and concern other states, but recently they have been published by non-governmental organisations in response to certain laws and trends in the United States.
