Blocking Critics on Facebook: Don't run for public office if you can't stand criticism
The father of our country knew what bad publicity was.
The Americans loved George Washington, but the newspapers soon began criticizing him for all possible domestic politics, always on his political principles.
Criticism must have been annoying,
But he did not silence his critics.
"If freedom of speech is removed, we may be led dumb and quiet like sheep for slaughter," Washington said in 1783.
That brings us to the governor of Maryland, Larry Hogan, who should learn from Washington.
Hogan's staff has removed at least 450 comments from his official Facebook page and blocked them.
The U.S. Civil Rights Union sued Hogan earlier this week.
His staff found the challenge to be unjustified, and the attitude was underestimating also online.
"What's the difference? This is just Facebook," a lot of people commented.
But it matters,
Especially in Hogan's case.
Hogan is an amazingly popular Republican governor of a Democratic state.
He has received the second best estimates of his operations among 50 governors.
Hogan is not sensitive to hotheads.
He has led the state firmly and has adhered strictly to the principles.
He has also used Facebook as the main channel of communication with his voters, and there he published a picture of a head bald in chemotherapy.
That is why blocking users entering the governor's Facebook page is unnecessary and even dangerous, and the governor's website is a public and official forum that his staff maintains with tax funds.
Hogan's spokesman, Amelia Chase, defended the governor's actions in an interview with Washington Post, who said it was just about moderating comments.
But branding commentators as trolls, spammers or haters is too easy.
The Washington Post interviewed people who were blocked by Hogan on Facebook.
They turned out to be ordinary people who wanted to talk to the leaders they chose, not trolls, but teachers, entrepreneurs and pastors, for example.
They said their comments were respectful, considerate and proper.
In his comment, the pastor quoted the Bible; he wanted to appeal to Hogan's Catholic faith.
Lawyer Lakshmi Sarma Ramani of Maryland Bowie was not hostile but asked about hate crimes.
"I politely said I was disappointed that Hogan had not taken a stand on hate crimes and other recent news," he wrote in the comments on the Washington Post report.
"I also cannot accept that when more people comment on the same thing, they are immediately considered to be an organized group and ignored as a large group of concerned citizens."
The governor's staff called the comments a "focused attack", and someone else might call them a move to promote what was considered important.
In the Facebook era, communication is easy to manage by blocking a critic or removing a critical comment.
In the old days, we should have sent staff to collect and burn newspapers with critical editorials, or arrested and silenced protesters.
But the truth is it's the same thing, now it's just digitally.
Hogan is not the first public official accused of chaining Facebook and other social media channels.
Twitter users blocked by President Trump have sued him.
The first major decision was taken last week in Virginia.
Alexandria District Court Judge James C. Cacheris said the Loudou district government violated the first amendment of the U.S. constitution by blocking the voter on Facebook.
And the U.S. Civil Rights Association went to talk to Kentucky Republican Governor Matt Bevin about using Twitter and Facebook.
This shouldn't be hard.
In Washington's time, cheap postage had a similar effect to the internet today.
The number of newspapers quadrupled from 1776 to 1800, and anonymous writers hammered Washington.
Even then there were trolls.
The nicknames Juricola, Valerius, Belisarius, and Portius wrote letters to newspapers calling Washington's decisions into question.
The president's office was flooded with appeals criticising Jay's contract, the US-British cooperation, trade and shipping agreement, as evidenced by the documents collected by the Papers of George Washington network project.
But he did not silence his critics.
Freedom of speech, freedom of opinion and freedom of conversation are the foundation stones of our nation.
Real leadership means accepting this fact.
