Poverty and Death in Indonesia's Gold Land
Bardina Degei does not use a stove for cooking.
Even the boiler is rarely used.
Degei lives in a wooden building in Enarotali, the capital of the Paniai region, located in Indonesia's restless Papua province, and when he prepares dinner, he usually puts a sweet potato - locally "not" - directly into the fireplace.
Half an hour later, the sweet potato burned to the ground will be devoured with bare, unwashed hands.
There are no furniture in Degei's home, sitting on a muddy floor, where he usually also does his daily chores, such as washing in murky water from a nearby swamp.
The toilet is provided by a bucket in a roofing room.
Degei is the youngest of her husband's four wives and has not been assigned fields to be treated.
Polygamy is common here.
Working late can be dangerous: most of the men in the village are unemployed, and many drink a lot, and soldiers must be taken into account.
"No one dares walk in the village after five at night," Degei says.
This is a rare peek into everyday life in Papuan highlands, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969, preceded by a controversial referendum in which 1,026 villages were forced to vote publicly in front of the occupying forces.
The local independence movement, which opposed the Dutch power, quickly turned its anger on Jakarta's government, which is holding the area under strict control and preventing foreign journalists and human rights observers from entering it.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, and the eastern part of the island belongs to Papua New Guinea.
Enarotali is remote and crass, and the journey begins on a one-and-a-half-hour flight from the province's capital Jayapura to Nabire, and continues on a five-hour driving trip with a rental car.
There is no public transport here.
The town of about 19,000 people has wooden houses surrounded by bamboos, whose corrugated roofs have been dyed into yellow browns by rust.
Few Indonesians have been here, not to mention journalists and foreigners.
Before the Christian missionaries came, Papuan Mee Pago tribe worshiped the god Uga Tamee.
Other changes have also taken place.
"We didn't have clothes like this," Degei says. He means a colorful hand-woven tapering cap, a dark skirt and a brightly colored blouse.
"In the past, all we had were leaves covered in our bodies."
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, with 28 percent of its inhabitants living below the poverty line, and child mortality and illiteracy are among the highest in Asia.
But it is also Indonesia's golden land.
Paniai is a highland area about the size of New Jersey, with a population of 153,000, just a hundred kilometres from Pania, the largest and most profitable gold mine in the world, owned by Freeport McMoran, based in Phoenix, USA.
In 2015, the mine produced $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper for Freeport.
In addition, Papua has an estimated $78 billion in wood reserves.
For the Papuans, however, these riches bring misery, as they mean the suffocating presence of a strong Indonesian army.
In 2005, the New York Times revealed that Freeport paid local military personnel and military local units nearly $20 million between 1998 and 2004, paying individual officers up to $150,000.
Papua's demands for greater self-determination threaten this source of income and are silenced without mercy.
According to human rights activists, since 1969 the Indonesian army has killed more than 500,000 beanmen and raped, tortured and imprisoned thousands.
According to the Asian Commission for Human Rights, mass killings in the highlands of Papuan tribes in the 1970s took on the proportions of genocide.
Last year the Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 people in the area during peaceful demonstrations.
The report by Brisbane Archdiocese We Will Lose Everything 2016 contains stories of previous year's atrocities, such as executions without trial, torture - rape and electrocution are particularly popular methods - and ruthless attacks towards peaceful demonstrations.
"It's hard to calculate the number of victims because there are weekly cases," Andreas Harsono, Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
The screws have been tightened as Papua's natural resources attract migrants from other parts of Indonesia.
Of the 3.5 million inhabitants of the province, 83 percent are Christians, but the demographic structure is changing as Indonesia's populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawes move Muslims to the region in the hope of a better livelihood.
Java-basedwarung food stalls sell fried chicken and gado-gado vegetables in peanut sauce.
It's hard for the locals to compete.
"The movers have started selling chicken and vegetables in the market place cheaper than the locals," says 24-year-old Abeth You, who comes from Paniai and moved to the province's capital for work.
"Local women lost their customers."
Indonesia's President Joko Widodo – called Jokowi – promised in his 2014 election campaign to tackle Papuan injustices and human rights violations.
Papua consists of 29 areas, and this former carpenter won the vote in 27 areas, including Paniai, on his way to the presidential castle of Jakarta.
But little has changed in Papua, and the locals feel betrayed.
"Our hearts were broken because we voted for Jokowi in 2014 and waited for him to fulfill our wish and restore justice," You said.
The Pania experienced some kind of wavebed just two months after Jokowi's inaugural ceremony in October.
Eleven children were singing carols at a fire in Enarotali on 7 December 2014, when two Indonesian soldiers appeared from the dark on motorcycles.
The frightened children told the soldiers that they should use headlights.
One of the soldiers did not like the remark, according to local pastor Yavedt Tebai, the man returned with four soldiers.
According to the victims and witnesses' reports, drunken soldiers caught the children and beat them with rifles.
That's how one of the soldiers fired at the children.
One of the children, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, fell into a coma as a result of assault.
A couple of hours later, the state election board building near the scene was set on fire, and the next day began to happen.
