The new results of the Swedish asylum seekers' age tests were announced
The latest results of the Swedish asylum seekers' medical age tests have been released, and the results of the new evaluation method reveal that over 80 per cent of those tested were found to be over 18 years old, but not everyone thinks the tests are reliable.
The Swedish National Bureau of Legal Medicine began testing earlier this year.
The tests can be used to assess the asylum seeker's age more closely, and a new test was introduced after the Swedish Immigration Service was criticised for failing to identify the actual age of applicants claiming to be minors.
The Finnish Immigration Service has carried out 6,880 tests so far, and the forensics office has now released the results of 2,481 tests, which were carried out between mid-March and the end of July 2017.
Eighty per cent of those tested, i.e. in 2002, the asylum seeker was determined to be over 18 years old, and in 25 cases, the Department of Law Medicine determined that the test was "possibly 18 years old or older."
In 432 cases, it was concluded that the asylum seeker is "possibly under 18 years old".
The tests were carried out only in cases where there was reason to doubt the age indicated by the applicant.
Johan Göransson from the Department of Law Medicine says that the results are consistent with the results of previous months.
"The numbers are quite uniform, and there are no significant differences in the statistics of the previous months," he told The Local.
While most of the applicants were determined to be over 18, that does not necessarily mean that the applicants lied about their age.
In May, the agency released the results of the 581 tests and reported that 442 cases had "refers to the fact that the study is 18 years old or older."
When Svenska Dagbladet examined the same results, it turned out that in 243 cases the applicant had openly told that he was turning 18 this year.
The medical age assessment method used in the tests takes X-rays of wisdom teeth and MRIs of knee joints, then the images are analysed by dentists and radiologists, and the method has also been criticised.
One of the sceptics is Karolininen Institute's endocrinologist Claude Marcus, whose work includes assessing people's biological maturity, which can be used to determine whether a person has entered puberty earlier or later than usual.
"I have had reason to think about it, and I think the method used is not the right one.
The definition of biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can't determine the age for sure, we shouldn't pretend we can," he said to Metro newspaper.
However, Göransson, a forensics agency, defended the accuracy of the tests: "It is common to say that the risk of determining a child as an adult is small.
The risk is the greatest in a situation where the test is about to turn 18, and the risk is about 10 per cent."
