NHS agreed to fund the experiment after the Court of Appeal upheld last year's Supreme Court ruling that NHS is able to pay for the drug PrEP, even though it is claimed to be funded by local authorities.
England's NHS leader Simon Stevens called the decision announced on Thursday a "significant new intervention", and the National AIDS Association described it as a "opening moment."
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be the first to start signing up for an experiment that will expand to other clinics in October, reaching its full range in England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) should be taken before sexual intercourse to reduce the risk of infection.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV infections in high-risk groups.
A drug taken before sexual intercourse means that there are enough drugs in the body to prevent HIV infection during sexual intercourse.
The medicine can be taken daily or two hours before sex.
The treatment target group includes gay men, bisexual men and transgenders, as well as people with HIV-positive partners who do not receive effective treatment.
The clinics choose eligible candidates for the experiment from men, women and transgenders, as well as those whose HIV-positive partner is not known to receive antiretroviral treatment for their disease.
People living in England and registered for general medical care can also apply for a trial at their local sexual health clinic.
The programme costs £10 million, and England's NHS signed a contract for medicines this week after an international tender.
The purpose of the experiment is to assess the potential of PrEP by gathering extensive clinical evidence about its targeting, taking and treatment implementation.
"This significant new intervention should complement and intensify the already existing diverse and increasingly effective ways of preventing HIV," Stevens said.
"It is yet another significant achievement in the struggle of more than 30 years to solve one of humanity's biggest health challenges."
"This is a crucial moment in the fight against HIV," said Deborah Gold, director of the national AIDS organisation.
"If PrEP is properly targeted at those in need and at risk, it can have a revolutionary effect on the HIV epidemic in England.
