This was welcome news."
"The most important thing now is to ensure that the experiment is launched quickly across the country and that no one at risk is excluded from it," said Ian Green, director of Terrence Higgins Foundation.
"The PrEP drug used in the experiment has been acquired, and we will soon be able to protect 10,000 people at risk from HIV infection."
"The start of the PrEP trial is a welcome event that lasted for several months because of the government's slow-down," says Sharon Hodgson, shadow government health minister.
"We have evidence that the drug can have a revolutionary effect on our work to prevent HIV and stop the spread of this threatening disease.
