When Ferrell drove towards Ferguson with their daughter in a flower dress and a crown matching it, they had another conversation about "what it's like to live black and under what conditions," and they had talked about it countless times before that morning.
"Do you remember when I told you how black people have had to fight for the things they believe in?" Ferrell remembers saying to his daughter.
"We're going to Ferguson because the police killed an 18-year-old boy, and that's not right."
"I couldn't stop taking my daughter with me," Ferrell said later.
"Today's events are... the culmination of events in the past.
My daughter has a right to know that and to grow into it.
He needs to be able to act and organize, but he also needs to know the different layers and conditions of the black experience, and he needs to know what we have to do to be freed, to free ourselves.
Fortunately, though I have been able to protect him from blatant racism, he is still like all the other black girls.
I feel like I would hurt him if I protected him from reality."
Their first stop in Ferguson was South Florissant Road, opposite the police station, which became a campground for activists, waiting for information about the case and finally finding out there would be no charge against the police.
From there, Ferrell and his daughter went to help a local entrepreneur who made lunch packages.
They packed lunches in bags and distributed them to protesters.
Ferrell gradually began to view activism in a new way.
"My activism changed completely after 9 August," he said. While studying at Missouri University in St. Louis, Ferrell was the chairman of the Association of Minority Nurse Students, at which time he focused on food law and health differences in black communities.
"I had no experience of organizing.
Somehow it just happened."
Weeks later, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, an assistant director of the documentary, in an evening demonstration.
Folayan said he and photographer Lucas Alvarado-Farrar "just wanted to tell," what was happening.
Ferrelli's mind was squirming with doubt, and he asked: "Do you really want to tell me what is going on, or do you want a story that you can take advantage of?"
The suspicion was based on the countless times that people, usually white people, had appeared in the local community to benefit from its difficulties and perseverance.
"We had heard that those born and raised in Ferguson did not have a common voice," Folayan recently said in an interview. "We wanted to do things differently."
Folayan had already contacted Assistant Director Damon Davis, who is known for his activism among sentenced prisoners.
Davis' involvement led Ferrell to join the project together with six other locals, and the film group followed the events during the years that followed Brown's shooting.
"This is not a documentary where someone speaks to us or speaks for us, but we do," Davis says.
"The most important thing for me was how local people are presented in the film, because I'm shown the same way."
According to Folayan, the intention was not to focus on Ferrell's experiences, because it was wanted to show that the popular movement "is not about charismatic leadership, it is about the community", but Ferrell proved to be the most open one to describe.
That's why the documentary shows surprisingly private aspects of Ferrell's life, such as falling in love and getting married.
"I felt pretty naked," Ferrell laughs when he tells how it felt to see the film for the first time.
"But I understood that this work and the human imagery of black people require a certain vulnerability."
In addition, Ferrell's story goes on to re-focus the role of black queer women in the wider Black Lives Matter movement.
The movement was born in the social media (#BlackLivesMatter) after the police had shot the black teenage boy Trayvon Martin in 2012, two of the three founders of the movement identify with the Queer identity.
