Red meat, dairy products and chocolate may relieve irritable bowel syndrome
Red meat and chocolate may sound like a nightmare in the digestive system.
However, a recent study claims the opposite: a diet rich in meat protein and dairy products may help to relieve irritable bowel syndrome.
Irritated bowel syndrome is an incurable disease that affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the UK, causing stomach cramps, swelling, repeated or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
People with IRR are usually advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but Washington University researchers found that the essential amino acid tryptophan in the protein helps the body to develop immune cells that strengthen intestinal tolerance.
According to the research director Marco Colonna, immune cells guard from the swamp and ensure that harmful microbes hiding in food do not enter the body.
Cells that cause inflammation are balanced by cells that strengthen tolerance, protecting the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance falls too close to the inflammation, the result may be irritable bowel syndrome.
The tests found that the immune cells that strengthen tolerance are found in mice that have a specific bacteria in their intestines.
The bacteria in question need tryptophan to make immune cells appear, and tryptophan is one of the ingredients of proteins.
"We found a connection between the development of the bacterium Lactobacillus reuteri and the development of cells that promote tolerance.
"The more tryptophan there was in mice' diet, the more such immune cells they had."
If the same works in humans, a combination of Lactobacillus reuteri and a diet rich in tryptophan can strengthen intestinal tolerance and reduce susceptibility to inflammation.
While studying immune cells that strengthen tolerance, researcher Luisa Cervantes-Barragan found that although one group of mice had such cells, they were not found in mice of the same mouse species that were kept separate from the other group.
He suspected that the difference was related to the microbes in the intestines of mice, the normal gastrointestinal community of bacteria, mushrooms and viruses.
When the DNA of the intestines of mice was examined, six bacterial species were found in mice with immune cells but not in other mice.
When Lactobacillus reuteri was given to mice that grew up in a sterile environment without intestinal microbes and did not develop immune cells, immune cells began to appear.
The researchers wanted to find out how bacteria affect the immune system, which raised the bacteria called Lactobacillus reuteri in liquid and transferred small amounts of fluid - without bacteria - to immature immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells developed into cells that strengthen tolerance.
When the active ingredient was purified from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism known as indoli-3 lactic acid.
When researchers doubled tryptophan levels in mice' diet, the number of cells that strengthen tolerance increased by about 50 percent, and when tryptophan levels were halved, the number dropped to half the previous.
According to Cervantes-Barragan, a person has the same tolerance-enhanced cells as a mouse, and most of us have Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not yet known whether the by-products of tryptophan from Lactobacillus reuteri are causing the cells to develop in humans in the same way as mice, but genetic defects associated with tryptophan have been observed in patients with irritable bowel syndrome.
"We probably want to promote the development of such cells because they regulate inflammation inside the intestines," Cervantes-Barragan said.
"High tryptophan levels, combined with the reutery of Lactobacillus, may contribute to their spread."
