"I just wanted to make sure you were aware of this because it is an exceptional event that gets a lot of visibility," the HMX-1 unit commander wrote in an e-mail the day before the event to his supervisor, who is an assistant commander for the naval flight.
The message said the helicopter would arrive on the southern lawn around 17 July at 7 a.m. and the event would begin at 3 p.m. and the helicopter would not leave until after the grass field was cleared in the evening between 6 and 9 p.m.
