The original crew was in the helicopter during the event, and the unit's security personnel were at the helicopter when it was on the ground.
It is not clear from the documents received by TIME whether another crew was eventually needed.
The U.S. Hatch Act prohibits federal workers from using state property for political purposes.
According to the documents, HMX-1 inquired whether the event was breaking the law.
"One of our questions was whether this was a violation of the Hatch Act, and we were told there was no violation," the commander wrote.
"It sounds like you can take part," the deputy commander replied.
Made in America was the official event of the White House, so it was not covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political tone.
At the event, the president spoke out in favour of the health reform that was being discussed in the Senate at the time, as well as in favour of looser state regulation.
The use of Marine One helicopter and Air Force One for political purposes is not a new phenomenon.
The presidents must use them on their journeys,
but using them only for photos is unusual.
Trump's actions attracted attention in February when Air Force One rolled the presidential campaign event back in Melbourne, Florida, and Trump has strongly criticised the use of his predecessor's presidential plane on Twitter.
"The White House is very pleased with the Made in America event, where American workers presented products made from American materials from all 50 states," said White House press secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews regularly conduct training flights in the Washington area and train on the southern grass field to bring the president to the White House with a centimetre accuracy.
