According to one official, flights to Made in America were part of the crew's monthly training quota.
The unit's helicopters also flew 11 hours that day in "non-presidential support missions".
According to the White House, the event did not cost taxpayers any other expenses.
Sikorsky's spokesman said the company was not involved in organising a helicopter demonstration on the southern grass court of the White House.
HMX-1 has no records of flights related to the president's duties, and it is difficult to accurately estimate the costs of the event.
According to the Ministry of Defence's 2017 hourly compensations, the VH-3D helicopter's compensation level is $24 380 per flight hour.
According to the documents from HMX-1, flights from Quantico base in Virginia to the White House and back took a total of an hour.
According to the White House, the helicopter's operating costs are clearly lower.
"It is misleading to calculate the cost to taxpayers according to the level of compensation," Walters said.
"The estimated level of compensation includes staff, maintenance and many other so-called sunk costs that will be taken into account in the annual appropriations."
According to a 2015 study carried out by RAND research company, compensation levels do not include personnel costs, but take into account fuel, maintenance and contract costs.
At the time of the event, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of the helicopter in the event.
