Now: Trump's phone calls were made up - White House spokesman: "I wouldn't say it was a lie"
The White House admits that two calls mentioned by US President Donald Trump never happened, reports the New York Times.
Trump's smoking calls with both the Mexican president and the head of a Boy Scout organization have proved to be made up.
White House spokesman Sarah Huckabee Sanders confirmed that there had been no calls.
But he said Trump wasn't lying.
According to Sanders, many of the scout leaders spoke to Trump personally, and Trump, with Mexico's President Enrique Pena Nieto, had spoken at the G20 meeting in Hamburg.
I wouldn't say it was a lie, it's a pretty big accusation.
Those conversations happened, not just on the phone, but in person, Sanders explained.
A speech to Boy Scouts sparked disapproval
On Monday, Mr. Trump said the President of Mexico called him and praised Mr. Trump's success in eliminating illegal immigration.
Mr. Trump said Pena Nieto said that few will cross the southern border of Mexico any more, because they know the journey will be blocked to the US border anyway.
On Wednesday, the Mexican government published a press release saying that there was no such call.
On Tuesday, Politico published a complete version of Trump's interview with The Wall Street Journal.
In it, Trump praised his speech at a large meeting of the National Scout organization in West Virginia.
I got a call from the Boy Scout leader, he said it was the greatest speech they've ever had.
They were very grateful, Trump said.
On Wednesday, the Boy Scouts' Association announced that it is not aware of a call from any of its leaders to Trump.
According to the press release, Michael Surbaugh, the director of the organization's earlier statement, in which he had apologized to the Boy Scouts for Trump's speech, speaks for himself.
Trump's speech at the Boy Scouts' Association's meeting caused a lot of confusion, as it was exceptionally political in nature.
Among other things, he praised the results of last autumn's presidential election.
